{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6535e4c9-71f5-46ea-876e-4754826f225b","content":"Here are the **3 key performance anti-patterns** in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. 🐌 Recursive wildcard glob (line 9, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` forces MSBuild to enumerate **every file** in the entire directory tree on every evaluation. This is the most expensive pattern here — evaluation happens frequently (IDE load, restore, build).\n\n### 2. 🐌 File I/O via property function (line 13, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))\n```\nReading file contents into a property during evaluation is costly. Evaluation is meant to be fast metadata resolution — disk I/O defeats that. This runs every time the project is evaluated, not just at build time.\n\n### 3. 🐌 3-level deep import chain\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import requires file resolution, I/O, and XML parsing during evaluation. This chain is 3 levels deep and could be flattened. Deep import chains compound evaluation cost, especially when repeated across many projects in a solution.\n\n---\n\n### Recommendations\n| Issue | Fix |\n|---|---|\n| Recursive glob | Scope to specific extensions/folders, e.g. `*.cs` or `src\\**\\*.cs` |\n| `ReadAllText` in property | Move to a build target (runs once at build, not evaluation) |\n| Nested imports | Flatten into a single `.props` file or reduce depth |\n\nThe recursive glob and the `ReadAllText` are the highest-impact issues — they add I/O to every evaluation cycle.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5aa81aaa-c66b-42d4-b786-ce29d251431c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project.\n\nKey issues I see:\n\n1. **Deeply nested import chain**: `EvalHeavy.csproj` → `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props`. This creates a 3-level deep import chain that MSBuild must resolve during evaluation. Each import requires file I/O and parsing.\n\n2. **Overly broad glob pattern**: `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" ...>` — This is a recursive wildcard glob that scans the entire directory tree. Even with the `Exclude` for bin/obj, MSBuild must enumerate every file in the project tree during evaluation. This is a well-known performance anti-pattern.\n   \n3. **File I/O during evaluation via property function**: Reading an entire file into a property during evaluation is expensive because property functions that perform I/O run frequently across IDE operations, restores, and builds.\n\n4. **Import placement**: The import is positioned after the initial property group but before item groups. While not ideal, SDK-style projects typically handle imports through Directory.Build.props or the SDK itself.","outputTokens":759,"requestId":"1411:13072B:265D3EC:2B84FFE:69EC1900"},"id":"e08fe9eb-94ed-43cb-930e-bc2b54ae4f6a","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:29:55.182Z","parentId":"43ac5bda-bdc5-4bea-b698-3922769142cf"}
